sec.p:
In a similar fashion to the phase–space portrait reconstruction method, proposed by Takens,19 the SDP mapping requested the reading of the signal (the pressure signal) with a constant delay time, called time lag. The pressure–time sampled data were used to construct two vectors of coordinates, representing the metrics of the modified phase–space portrait to transform the signal from 1D time axis to a 2D polar space. The SDP phase–space portrait metric is given in Table 2 and the SDP mapping is illustrated in Figure 7.
Figure 7.
SDP phase–space portrait mapping.

Table 2.
SDP phase–space portrait metric.





i=0,Nti+1=ti+Lσi=σ(ti)σi+1=σ(ti+1)=σ(ti+L)Ri=fR(σi)=σi-σΣ-σΘi±=fΘ(σi+1)=Θ0±σi+1-σΣ-σξ



in which:



i is the index of the dot;



L is the time lag coefficient;



σi, σi+1 are the sampled i-th, i-th+L signals;



Σ and σ are the highest and the lowest value of the original waveform window;



Θ0 is the angular position of the polar reference line of the pattern;



ξ is the gain of the plotting; and



Ri and Θi± are the coordinates of the space portrait.





SDP: symmetrised dot pattern.
